{{Infobox royalty | type = Sultan | name = Abu Abd Allah al-Sheikh Muhammad ibn Yahya | title = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | succession = Kingdom of Fez | reign = 1472-1504 | coronation = | predecessor1 = | successor1 = Abu Abd Allah al-Burtuqali Muhammad ibn Muhammad | spouse = | spouse-type = | issue = | house = [[Wattasid dynasty|Wattasid]] | house-type = Dynasty | father = Yahya ibn Abi Zakariya Yahya | mother = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = 1504 | death_place = | place of burial = | signature = | religion = [[Sunni Islam]] }}
'''Abu Abd Allah al-Sheikh Muhammad ibn Yahya''' (also known as '''Abu Abdellah al-Shaykh Muhammad ben Yehya''', '''Abu Abdallah Sheikh Muhammad ibn Yahya''' or '''Muhammad ibn Yahya al-Sheikh''') was the first [[Wattasid dynasty|Wattasid]] Sultan of Morocco and King of Fez between 1472 and 1504.<ref>{{cite book|first1=Muzaffar Husain|last1=Syed|first2=Syed Saud|last2=Akhtar|first3=B D|last3=Usmani|title=Concise History of Islam|year=2011|place=New Delhi|publisher=Vij Books|isbn=978-9381411094|page=150}}</ref>
==Background== Abu Abd Allah al-Sheikh Muhammad ibn Yahya was born into the powerful Wattasid family that had ruled the eastern [[Rif]] from Tazouta (near present-day [[Nador]]) since the late 13th century. While theoretically subject to the [[Marinid dynasty|Marinid]] sultans, they were largely autonomous. By the start of the 15th Century, the Wattasids had accumulated power while the Merinids were distracted attempting to repel Portuguese and Spanish invasions with the [[Emirate of Granada|Granadans]]. When [[Abd al-Haqq II]] came to power at the age of one in 1421, they held the regency, which they continued to hold when Abd al-Haqq II came of age.<ref>{{cite book|first=Charles-André|last=Julien|title=Histoire de l'Afrique du Nord, des origines à 1830|publisher=Payot|place=Paris|year=1994|isbn=9782228887892|page=196}}</ref> In 1459, Abd al-Haqq II ordered the slaughter of the Wattasids, leaving Abu Abd Allah al-Sheikh Muhammad ibn Yahya one of the few of his family left alive.
==Rise to Power== In the chaos that followed the [[1465 Moroccan revolt]], Abu Abd Allah al-Sheikh Muhammad ibn Yahya fought against the Joutey branch of the [[Idrisid]]s. In 1471, he defeated their leader, Muhammad ibn Ali Amrani-Joutey, who had declared himself Sultan. He went on to rule the [[Kingdom of Fez]] which controlled the northern part of Morocco.
==Succession== He was succeeded by his son Abu Abd Allah al-Burtuqali Muhammad ibn Muhammad.
