{{Infobox writer | name = al-Akhtal | image = | caption = | birth_date = 19/640 | birth_place = [[Al-Hirah]] or [[Sergiopolis]] | death_date = 92/708 | occupation = [[Poet]] | genre = [[Panegyric]], [[Satire]] | notableworks = ''[[Khaffa al-Qatîn]]''
}}
'''Ghiyath b. Ghawth b. al-Salt b. al-Tariqa al-Taghlibi''', commonly known as '''al-Akhtal''' (The Loquacious), was one of the most famous [[Arab]] poets of the [[Umayyad]] period. He belonged to the [[Banu Taghlib]] tribe, and was, like his fellow-tribesmen, a [[Monophysite Christian|Christian]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Esat|first=AYYILDIZ|date=2017|title=El-Ahtal'ın Emevilere methiyeleri|url=http://dergiler.ankara.edu.tr/dergiler/26/2238/23239.pdf|journal=Ankara Üniversitesi Dil ve Tarih-Coğrafya Fakültesi Dergisi - DTCF Dergisi|volume=57|issue=2|pages=936–960|doi=10.1501/dtcfder_0000001545|issn=2459-0150}}</ref>.
==Biography== al-Akhtal al-Taghlibî was one of the great panegyrists of the Umayyad period. He became famous for his satires and panegyrics in a period when poetry was an important political instrument. al-Akhtal was introduced to [[Yazid I|Yazîd b. Muʿâwiyah]] by [[Ka‘b b. Ju‘ayl]]. He became a close friend of the crown prince. [[Yazid I|Yazîd]], when he succeeded to the throne, was very kind to al-Akhtal. Although he was Christian, he was favoured by leading Umayyad caliphs. All his life al-Akhtal followed the reigning Umayyad Dynasty<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Esat|first=AYYILDIZ|date=2017|title=El-Ahtal'ın Emevilere methiyeleri|url=http://dergiler.ankara.edu.tr/dergiler/26/2238/23239.pdf|journal=Ankara Üniversitesi Dil ve Tarih-Coğrafya Fakültesi Dergisi - DTCF Dergisi|volume=57|issue=2|pages=936–960|doi=10.1501/dtcfder_0000001545|issn=2459-0150}}</ref>.
He lauded in his panegyrics Yazîd, [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan|ʿAbd al-Malik b. Marwân]] and [[Al-Walid I|al-Walîd b. ʿAbd al-Malik]] and in his satires attacked all opponents of the caliphs. al-Akhtal became official poet to the caliph [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan|‘Abd al-Malik]], to whom he dedicated a number of panegyrics. But he fell into disfavour under [[Al-Walid I|Walîd I]]. The pre-Islamic bedouin tradition is always apparent in the poems of al-Akhtal and his panegyrics show the continued vitality of this tradition. The panegyrics of al-Akhtal acquired a classical status. His poetry was accepted by critics as source of pure Arabic<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Esat|first=AYYILDIZ|date=2017|title=El-Ahtal'ın Emevilere methiyeleri|url=http://dergiler.ankara.edu.tr/dergiler/26/2238/23239.pdf|journal=Ankara Üniversitesi Dil ve Tarih-Coğrafya Fakültesi Dergisi - DTCF Dergisi|volume=57|issue=2|pages=936–960|doi=10.1501/dtcfder_0000001545|issn=2459-0150}}</ref>.
Of al-Akhtal's private life few details are known, save that he was married and divorced, and that he spent part of his time in [[Damascus]], part with his tribe in Mesopotamia. In the [[Qays–Yaman rivalry#Ayyam raids|Taghlib–Qays war]] he participated on the battlefield, as well as by his [[satire]]s.{{sfn|Thatcher|1911}} In the literary strife between his contemporaries [[Jarir ibn Atiyah]] and [[Farazdaq]], Akhtal was induced to support the latter poet. Al-Akhtal, Jarir and Farazdaq form a trio celebrated among the Arabs, but as to superiority there is dispute. [[Abu Ubaidah (scholar)|Abu ʿUbaidah]] placed him highest of the three on the ground that among his [[poem]]s there were ten flawless [[qasida]]s, and ten more nearly so, and that this could not be said of the other two.{{sfn|Thatcher|1911}}
==Works== ''The Poetry of al-Akhtal'' has been published at the Jesuit press in Beirūt, 1891. A full account of the poet and his times is given in H. Lammens’ ''Le chantre des Omiades'' (Paris, 1895) (a reprint from the ''Journal Asiatique'' for 1894).{{sfn|Thatcher|1911}}
